9 // This class implements a command line argument processor that is useful when ----
10 // creating a tool. It provides a simple, minimalistic interface that is easily ----
11 // extensible and supports nonlocal (library) command line options. ----
12 // ----
13 // Note that rather than trying to figure out what this code does, you could try ----
14 // reading the library documentation located in docs/CommandLine.html ----
15 // ----
16 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----

813 static bool isWhitespace(char C) { 0
814 return C == ' ' || C == '\t' || C == '\r' || C == '\n'; 0
815 } ----
816 ----
817 static bool isWhitespaceOrNull(char C) { 0
818 return isWhitespace(C) || C == '\0'; 0

822 ----
823 void cl::TokenizeGNUCommandLine(StringRef Src, StringSaver &Saver, 0
824 SmallVectorImpl &NewArgv, ----
825 bool MarkEOLs) { ----
826 SmallString<128> Token; 0
827 for (size_t I = 0, E = Src.size(); I != E; ++I) { 0
828 // Consume runs of whitespace. ----
829 if (Token.empty()) { 0
830 while (I != E && isWhitespace(Src[I])) { 0
831 // Mark the end of lines in response files. ----
832 if (MarkEOLs && Src[I] == '\n') 0
833 NewArgv.push_back(nullptr); 0
834 ++I; 0
835 } ----
836 if (I == E) 0
837 break; 0
838 } ----
839 ----
840 char C = Src[I]; 0
841 ----
842 // Backslash escapes the next character. ----
843 if (I + 1 < E && C == '\\') { 0
844 ++I; // Skip the escape. 0
845 Token.push_back(Src[I]); 0
846 continue; 0
847 } ----
848 ----
849 // Consume a quoted string. ----
850 if (isQuote(C)) { 0
851 ++I; 0
852 while (I != E && Src[I] != C) { 0
853 // Backslash escapes the next character. ----
854 if (Src[I] == '\\' && I + 1 != E) 0
855 ++I; 0
856 Token.push_back(Src[I]); 0
857 ++I; 0
858 } ----
859 if (I == E) 0
860 break; 0
861 continue; 0
862 } ----
863 ----
864 // End the token if this is whitespace. ----
865 if (isWhitespace(C)) { 0
866 if (!Token.empty()) 0
867 NewArgv.push_back(Saver.save(Token.str()).data()); 0
868 // Mark the end of lines in response files. ----
869 if (MarkEOLs && C == '\n') 0
870 NewArgv.push_back(nullptr); 0
871 Token.clear(); 0
872 continue; 0
873 } ----
874 ----
875 // This is a normal character. Append it. ----
876 Token.push_back(C); 0
877 } ----
878 ----
879 // Append the last token after hitting EOF with no whitespace. ----
880 if (!Token.empty()) 0
881 NewArgv.push_back(Saver.save(Token.str()).data()); 0
882 } 0
883 ----
884 /// Backslashes are interpreted in a rather complicated way in the Windows-style ----
885 /// command line, because backslashes are used both to separate path and to ----
886 /// escape double quote. This method consumes runs of backslashes as well as the ----
887 /// following double quote if it's escaped. ----
888 /// ----
889 /// * If an even number of backslashes is followed by a double quote, one ----
890 /// backslash is output for every pair of backslashes, and the last double ----
891 /// quote remains unconsumed. The double quote will later be interpreted as ----
892 /// the start or end of a quoted string in the main loop outside of this ----
893 /// function. ----
894 /// ----
895 /// * If an odd number of backslashes is followed by a double quote, one ----
896 /// backslash is output for every pair of backslashes, and a double quote is ----
897 /// output for the last pair of backslash-double quote. The double quote is ----
898 /// consumed in this case. ----
899 /// ----
900 /// * Otherwise, backslashes are interpreted literally. ----
901 static size_t parseBackslash(StringRef Src, size_t I, SmallString<128> &Token) { 0
902 size_t E = Src.size(); 0
903 int BackslashCount = 0; 0
904 // Skip the backslashes. ----
905 do { ----
906 ++I; 0
907 ++BackslashCount; 0
908 } while (I != E && Src[I] == '\\'); 0
909 ----
910 bool FollowedByDoubleQuote = (I != E && Src[I] == '"'); 0
911 if (FollowedByDoubleQuote) { 0
912 Token.append(BackslashCount / 2, '\\'); 0
913 if (BackslashCount % 2 == 0) 0
914 return I - 1; 0
915 Token.push_back('"'); 0
916 return I; 0
917 } ----
918 Token.append(BackslashCount, '\\'); 0
919 return I - 1; 0
920 } ----
921 ----
922 // Windows treats whitespace, double quotes, and backslashes specially, except ----
923 // when parsing the first token of a full command line, in which case ----
924 // backslashes are not special. ----
925 static bool isWindowsSpecialChar(char C) { 0
926 return isWhitespaceOrNull(C) || C == '\\' || C == '\"'; 0
927 } ----
928 static bool isWindowsSpecialCharInCommandName(char C) { 0
929 return isWhitespaceOrNull(C) || C == '\"'; 0
930 } ----
931 ----
932 // Windows tokenization implementation. The implementation is designed to be ----
933 // inlined and specialized for the two user entry points. ----
934 static inline void tokenizeWindowsCommandLineImpl( 0
935 StringRef Src, StringSaver &Saver, function_ref AddToken, ----
936 bool AlwaysCopy, function_ref MarkEOL, bool InitialCommandName) { ----
937 SmallString<128> Token; 0
938 ----
939 // Sometimes, this function will be handling a full command line including an ----
940 // executable pathname at the start. In that situation, the initial pathname ----
941 // needs different handling from the following arguments, because when ----
942 // CreateProcess or cmd.exe scans the pathname, it doesn't treat \ as ----
943 // escaping the quote character, whereas when libc scans the rest of the ----
944 // command line, it does. ----
945 bool CommandName = InitialCommandName; 0
946 ----
947 // Try to do as much work inside the state machine as possible. ----
948 enum { INIT, UNQUOTED, QUOTED } State = INIT; 0
949 ----
950 for (size_t I = 0, E = Src.size(); I < E; ++I) { 0
951 switch (State) { 0
952 case INIT: { 0
953 assert(Token.empty() && "token should be empty in initial state"); 0
954 // Eat whitespace before a token. ----
955 while (I < E && isWhitespaceOrNull(Src[I])) { 0
956 if (Src[I] == '\n') 0
957 MarkEOL(); 0
958 ++I; 0
959 } ----
960 // Stop if this was trailing whitespace. ----
961 if (I >= E) 0
962 break; 0
963 size_t Start = I; 0
964 if (CommandName) { 0
965 while (I < E && !isWindowsSpecialCharInCommandName(Src[I])) 0
966 ++I; 0
967 } else { ----
968 while (I < E && !isWindowsSpecialChar(Src[I])) 0
969 ++I; 0
970 } ----
971 StringRef NormalChars = Src.slice(Start, I); 0
972 if (I >= E || isWhitespaceOrNull(Src[I])) { 0
973 // No special characters: slice out the substring and start the next ----
974 // token. Copy the string if the caller asks us to. ----
975 AddToken(AlwaysCopy ? Saver.save(NormalChars) : NormalChars); 0
976 if (I < E && Src[I] == '\n') { 0
977 MarkEOL(); 0
978 CommandName = InitialCommandName; 0
979 } else { ----
980 CommandName = false; 0
981 } ----
982 } else if (Src[I] == '\"') { 0
983 Token += NormalChars; 0
984 State = QUOTED; 0
985 } else if (Src[I] == '\\') { 0
986 assert(!CommandName && "or else we'd have treated it as a normal char"); 0
987 Token += NormalChars; 0
988 I = parseBackslash(Src, I, Token); 0
989 State = UNQUOTED; 0
990 } else { ----
991 llvm_unreachable("unexpected special character"); 0
992 } ----
993 break; 0
994 } ----
995 ----
996 case UNQUOTED: 0
997 if (isWhitespaceOrNull(Src[I])) { 0
998 // Whitespace means the end of the token. If we are in this state, the ----
999 // token must have contained a special character, so we must copy the ----
1000 // token. ----
1001 AddToken(Saver.save(Token.str())); 0
1002 Token.clear(); 0
1003 if (Src[I] == '\n') { 0
1004 CommandName = InitialCommandName; 0
1005 MarkEOL(); 0
1006 } else { ----
1007 CommandName = false; 0
1008 } ----
1009 State = INIT; 0
1010 } else if (Src[I] == '\"') { 0
1011 State = QUOTED; 0
1012 } else if (Src[I] == '\\' && !CommandName) { 0
1013 I = parseBackslash(Src, I, Token); 0
1014 } else { ----
1015 Token.push_back(Src[I]); 0
1016 } ----
1017 break; 0
1018 ----
1019 case QUOTED: 0
1020 if (Src[I] == '\"') { 0
1021 if (I < (E - 1) && Src[I + 1] == '"') { 0
1022 // Consecutive double-quotes inside a quoted string implies one ----
1023 // double-quote. ----
1024 Token.push_back('"'); 0
1025 ++I; 0
1026 } else { ----
1027 // Otherwise, end the quoted portion and return to the unquoted state. ----
1028 State = UNQUOTED; 0
1029 } ----
1030 } else if (Src[I] == '\\' && !CommandName) { 0
1031 I = parseBackslash(Src, I, Token); 0
1032 } else { ----
1033 Token.push_back(Src[I]); 0
1034 } ----
1035 break; 0
1036 } ----
1037 } ----
1038 ----
1039 if (State != INIT) 0
1040 AddToken(Saver.save(Token.str())); 0
1041 } 0
1042 ----
1043 void cl::TokenizeWindowsCommandLine(StringRef Src, StringSaver &Saver, 0
1044 SmallVectorImpl &NewArgv, ----
1045 bool MarkEOLs) { ----
1046 auto AddToken = [&](StringRef Tok) { NewArgv.push_back(Tok.data()); }; 0
1047 auto OnEOL = [&]() { 0
1048 if (MarkEOLs) 0

1052 /*AlwaysCopy=*/true, OnEOL, false); ----

1074 ----
1075 void cl::tokenizeConfigFile(StringRef Source, StringSaver &Saver, 0
1076 SmallVectorImpl &NewArgv, ----
1077 bool MarkEOLs) { ----
1078 for (const char *Cur = Source.begin(); Cur != Source.end();) { 0
1079 SmallString<128> Line; 0
1080 // Check for comment line. ----
1081 if (isWhitespace(*Cur)) { 0
1082 while (Cur != Source.end() && isWhitespace(*Cur)) 0
1083 ++Cur; 0
1084 continue; 0
1085 } ----
1086 if (*Cur == '#') { 0
1087 while (Cur != Source.end() && *Cur != '\n') 0
1088 ++Cur; 0
1089 continue; 0
1090 } ----
1091 // Find end of the current line. ----
1092 const char *Start = Cur; 0
1093 for (const char *End = Source.end(); Cur != End; ++Cur) { 0
1094 if (*Cur == '\\') { 0
1095 if (Cur + 1 != End) { 0
1096 ++Cur; 0
1097 if (*Cur == '\n' || 0
1098 (*Cur == '\r' && (Cur + 1 != End) && Cur[1] == '\n')) { 0
1099 Line.append(Start, Cur - 1); 0
1100 if (*Cur == '\r') 0
1101 ++Cur; 0
1102 Start = Cur + 1; 0
1103 } ----
1104 } ----
1105 } else if (*Cur == '\n') 0
1106 break; 0
1107 } ----
1108 // Tokenize line. ----
1109 Line.append(Start, Cur); 0
1110 cl::TokenizeGNUCommandLine(Line, Saver, NewArgv, MarkEOLs); 0
1111 } 0
1112 } 0
1113 ----
1114 // It is called byte order marker but the UTF-8 BOM is actually not affected ----
1115 // by the host system's endianness. ----
1116 static bool hasUTF8ByteOrderMark(ArrayRef S) { 0
1117 return (S.size() >= 3 && S[0] == '\xef' && S[1] == '\xbb' && S[2] == '\xbf'); 0
1118 } ----
1119 ----
1120 // Substitute with the file's base path. ----
1121 static void ExpandBasePaths(StringRef BasePath, StringSaver &Saver, 0
1122 const char *&Arg) { ----
1123 assert(sys::path::is_absolute(BasePath)); 0
1124 constexpr StringLiteral Token(""); 0
1125 const StringRef ArgString(Arg); 0
1126 ----
1127 SmallString<128> ResponseFile; 0
1128 StringRef::size_type StartPos = 0; 0
1129 for (StringRef::size_type TokenPos = ArgString.find(Token); 0
1130 TokenPos != StringRef::npos; 0
1131 TokenPos = ArgString.find(Token, StartPos)) { 0
1132 // Token may appear more than once per arg (e.g. comma-separated linker ----
1133 // args). Support by using path-append on any subsequent appearances. ----
1134 const StringRef LHS = ArgString.substr(StartPos, TokenPos - StartPos); 0
1135 if (ResponseFile.empty()) 0
1136 ResponseFile = LHS; 0
1137 else ----
1138 llvm::sys::path::append(ResponseFile, LHS); 0
1139 ResponseFile.append(BasePath); 0
1140 StartPos = TokenPos + Token.size(); 0
1141 } ----
1142 ----
1143 if (!ResponseFile.empty()) { 0
1144 // Path-append the remaining arg substring if at least one token appeared. ----
1145 const StringRef Remaining = ArgString.substr(StartPos); 0
1146 if (!Remaining.empty()) 0
1147 llvm::sys::path::append(ResponseFile, Remaining); 0
1148 Arg = Saver.save(ResponseFile.str()).data(); 0
1149 } ----
1150 } 0

1152 // FName must be an absolute path. ----
1153 Error ExpansionContext::expandResponseFile( 0
1154 StringRef FName, SmallVectorImpl &NewArgv) { ----
1155 assert(sys::path::is_absolute(FName)); 0
1156 llvm::ErrorOr> MemBufOrErr = ----
1157 FS->getBufferForFile(FName); 0
1158 if (!MemBufOrErr) { 0
1159 std::error_code EC = MemBufOrErr.getError(); 0
1160 return llvm::createStringError(EC, Twine("cannot not open file '") + FName + 0
1161 "': " + EC.message()); 0
1162 } ----
1163 MemoryBuffer &MemBuf = *MemBufOrErr.get(); 0
1164 StringRef Str(MemBuf.getBufferStart(), MemBuf.getBufferSize()); 0
1165 ----
1166 // If we have a UTF-16 byte order mark, convert to UTF-8 for parsing. ----
1167 ArrayRef BufRef(MemBuf.getBufferStart(), MemBuf.getBufferEnd()); 0
1168 std::string UTF8Buf; 0
1169 if (hasUTF16ByteOrderMark(BufRef)) { 0
1170 if (!convertUTF16ToUTF8String(BufRef, UTF8Buf)) 0
1171 return llvm::createStringError(std::errc::illegal_byte_sequence, ----
1172 "Could not convert UTF16 to UTF8"); 0
1173 Str = StringRef(UTF8Buf); 0
1174 } ----
1175 // If we see UTF-8 BOM sequence at the beginning of a file, we shall remove ----
1176 // these bytes before parsing. ----
1177 // Reference: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UTF-8#Byte_order_mark ----
1178 else if (hasUTF8ByteOrderMark(BufRef)) 0
1179 Str = StringRef(BufRef.data() + 3, BufRef.size() - 3); 0
1180 ----
1181 // Tokenize the contents into NewArgv. ----
1182 Tokenizer(Str, Saver, NewArgv, MarkEOLs); 0
1183 ----
1184 // Expanded file content may require additional transformations, like using ----
1185 // absolute paths instead of relative in '@file' constructs or expanding ----
1186 // macros. ----
1187 if (!RelativeNames && !InConfigFile) 0
1188 return Error::success(); 0
1189 ----
1190 StringRef BasePath = llvm::sys::path::parent_path(FName); 0
1191 for (const char *&Arg : NewArgv) { 0
1192 if (!Arg) 0
1193 continue; 0
1194 ----
1195 // Substitute with the file's base path. ----
1196 if (InConfigFile) 0
1197 ExpandBasePaths(BasePath, Saver, Arg); 0
1198 ----
1199 // Discover the case, when argument should be transformed into '@file' and ----
1200 // evaluate 'file' for it. ----
1201 StringRef ArgStr(Arg); 0
1202 StringRef FileName; 0
1203 bool ConfigInclusion = false; 0
1204 if (ArgStr.consume_front("@")) { 0
1205 FileName = ArgStr; 0
1206 if (!llvm::sys::path::is_relative(FileName)) 0
1207 continue; 0
1208 } else if (ArgStr.consume_front("--config=")) { 0
1209 FileName = ArgStr; 0
1210 ConfigInclusion = true; 0
1211 } else { ----
1212 continue; 0
1213 } ----
1214 ----
1215 // Update expansion construct. ----
1216 SmallString<128> ResponseFile; 0
1217 ResponseFile.push_back('@'); 0
1218 if (ConfigInclusion && !llvm::sys::path::has_parent_path(FileName)) { 0
1219 SmallString<128> FilePath; 0
1220 if (!findConfigFile(FileName, FilePath)) 0
1221 return createStringError( ----
1222 std::make_error_code(std::errc::no_such_file_or_directory), ----
1223 "cannot not find configuration file: " + FileName); 0
1224 ResponseFile.append(FilePath); 0
1225 } else { 0
1226 ResponseFile.append(BasePath); 0
1227 llvm::sys::path::append(ResponseFile, FileName); 0
1228 } ----
1229 Arg = Saver.save(ResponseFile.str()).data(); 0
1230 } 0
1231 return Error::success(); 0
1232 } 0

1234 /// Expand response files on a command line recursively using the given ----
1235 /// StringSaver and tokenization strategy. ----
1236 Error ExpansionContext::expandResponseFiles( 2 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1237 SmallVectorImpl &Argv) { ----
1238 struct ResponseFileRecord { ----
1239 std::string File; ----
1240 size_t End; ----
1241 }; ----
1242 ----
1243 // To detect recursive response files, we maintain a stack of files and the ----
1244 // position of the last argument in the file. This position is updated ----
1245 // dynamically as we recursively expand files. ----
1246 SmallVector FileStack; 2 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1247 ----
1248 // Push a dummy entry that represents the initial command line, removing ----
1249 // the need to check for an empty list. ----
1250 FileStack.push_back({"", Argv.size()}); 2 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1251 ----
1252 // Don't cache Argv.size() because it can change. ----
1253 for (unsigned I = 0; I != Argv.size();) { 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1254 while (I == FileStack.back().End) { 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1255 // Passing the end of a file's argument list, so we can remove it from the ----
1256 // stack. ----
1257 FileStack.pop_back(); 0
1258 } ----
1259 ----
1260 const char *Arg = Argv[I]; 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll

1263 ++I; 0

1265 } ----
1266 ----
1267 if (Arg[0] != '@') { 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1268 ++I; 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1269 continue; 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1270 } ----
1271 ----

1273 // Note that CurrentDir is only used for top-level rsp files, the rest will ----
1274 // always have an absolute path deduced from the containing file. ----
1275 SmallString<128> CurrDir; 0
1276 if (llvm::sys::path::is_relative(FName)) { 0
1277 if (CurrentDir.empty()) { 0
1278 if (auto CWD = FS->getCurrentWorkingDirectory()) { 0
1279 CurrDir = *CWD; 0
1280 } else { ----
1281 return createStringError( ----
1282 CWD.getError(), Twine("cannot get absolute path for: ") + FName); 0
1283 } 0
1284 } else { ----
1285 CurrDir = CurrentDir; 0
1286 } ----
1287 llvm::sys::path::append(CurrDir, FName); 0
1288 FName = CurrDir.c_str(); 0
1289 } ----
1290 ----

1292 if (!Res || !Res->exists()) { 0
1293 std::error_code EC = Res.getError(); 0

1295 // If the specified file does not exist, leave '@file' unexpanded, as ----
1296 // libiberty does. ----
1297 if (!EC || EC == llvm::errc::no_such_file_or_directory) { 0
1298 ++I; 0
1299 continue; 0
1300 } ----
1301 } ----
1302 if (!EC) 0
1303 EC = llvm::errc::no_such_file_or_directory; 0
1304 return createStringError(EC, Twine("cannot not open file '") + FName + 0
1305 "': " + EC.message()); 0
1306 } ----
1307 const llvm::vfs::Status &FileStatus = Res.get(); 0
1308 ----
1309 auto IsEquivalent = ----
1310 [FileStatus, this](const ResponseFileRecord &RFile) -> ErrorOr { 0
1311 ErrorOr RHS = FS->status(RFile.File); 0
1312 if (!RHS) 0
1313 return RHS.getError(); 0
1314 return FileStatus.equivalent(*RHS); 0
1315 }; 0
1316 ----
1317 // Check for recursive response files. ----
1318 for (const auto &F : drop_begin(FileStack)) { 0
1319 if (ErrorOr R = IsEquivalent(F)) { 0
1320 if (R.get()) 0
1321 return createStringError( ----
1322 R.getError(), Twine("recursive expansion of: '") + F.File + "'"); 0
1323 } else { ----
1324 return createStringError(R.getError(), ----
1325 Twine("cannot open file: ") + F.File); 0
1326 } 0
1327 } ----
1328 ----
1329 // Replace this response file argument with the tokenization of its ----
1330 // contents. Nested response files are expanded in subsequent iterations. ----
1331 SmallVector ExpandedArgv; 0
1332 if (Error Err = expandResponseFile(FName, ExpandedArgv)) 0
1333 return Err; 0
1334 ----
1335 for (ResponseFileRecord &Record : FileStack) { 0
1336 // Increase the end of all active records by the number of newly expanded ----
1337 // arguments, minus the response file itself. ----
1338 Record.End += ExpandedArgv.size() - 1; 0
1339 } ----
1340 ----
1341 FileStack.push_back({FName, I + ExpandedArgv.size()}); 0
1342 Argv.erase(Argv.begin() + I); 0
1343 Argv.insert(Argv.begin() + I, ExpandedArgv.begin(), ExpandedArgv.end()); 0
1344 } 0
1345 ----

1347 // stream. A failure here indicates a bug in the stack popping logic above. ----
1348 // Note that FileStack may have more than one element at this point because we ----
1349 // don't have a chance to pop the stack when encountering recursive files at ----
1350 // the end of the stream, so seeing that doesn't indicate a bug. ----
1351 assert(FileStack.size() > 0 && Argv.size() == FileStack.back().End); 2 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1352 return Error::success(); 2 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1353 } 2 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll

1391 bool ExpansionContext::findConfigFile(StringRef FileName, 0
1392 SmallVectorImpl &FilePath) { ----
1393 SmallString<128> CfgFilePath; 0

1395 auto Status = FS->status(Path); 0

1397 Status->getType() == llvm::sys::fs::file_type::regular_file; 0
1398 }; 0

1401 // configuration file. ----

1403 CfgFilePath = FileName; 0

1405 return false; 0

1413 for (const StringRef &Dir : SearchDirs) { 0
1414 if (Dir.empty()) 0
1415 continue; 0
1416 CfgFilePath.assign(Dir); 0
1417 llvm::sys::path::append(CfgFilePath, FileName); 0
1418 llvm::sys::path::native(CfgFilePath); 0
1419 if (FileExists(CfgFilePath)) { 0
1420 FilePath.assign(CfgFilePath.begin(), CfgFilePath.end()); 0
1421 return true; 0
1422 } ----
1423 } ----
1424 ----
1425 return false; 0
1426 } 0

2099 // Return the width of the option tag for printing... ----
2100 size_t generic_parser_base::getOptionWidth(const Option &O) const { 0
2101 if (O.hasArgStr()) { 0
2102 size_t Size = ----
2103 argPlusPrefixesSize(O.ArgStr) + EqValue.size(); 0
2104 for (unsigned i = 0, e = getNumOptions(); i != e; ++i) { 0
2105 StringRef Name = getOption(i); 0
2106 if (!shouldPrintOption(Name, getDescription(i), O)) 0
2107 continue; 0
2108 size_t NameSize = Name.empty() ? EmptyOption.size() : Name.size(); 0
2109 Size = std::max(Size, NameSize + getOptionPrefixesSize()); 0
2110 } ----
2111 return Size; 0
2112 } else { ----
2113 size_t BaseSize = 0; 0
2114 for (unsigned i = 0, e = getNumOptions(); i != e; ++i) 0
2115 BaseSize = std::max(BaseSize, getOption(i).size() + 8); 0
2116 return BaseSize; 0
2117 } ----
2118 } ----

2137 } ----

2140 Option::printHelpStr(O.HelpStr, GlobalWidth, 0
2141 EqValue.size() + 0

2149 outs() << OptionPrefix << OptionName; 0

2157 else ----

2159 } ----

2272 // Copy Options into a vector so we can sort them as we like. ----
2273 static void sortOpts(StringMap 0
2274 SmallVectorImpl> &Opts, ----
2275 bool ShowHidden) { ----
2276 SmallPtrSet 0
2277 ----
2278 for (StringMap 0
2279 I != E; ++I) { 0
2280 // Ignore really-hidden options. ----
2281 if (I->second->getOptionHiddenFlag() == ReallyHidden) 0
2282 continue; 0
2283 ----
2284 // Unless showhidden is set, ignore hidden flags. ----
2285 if (I->second->getOptionHiddenFlag() == Hidden && !ShowHidden) 0
2286 continue; 0
2287 ----
2288 // If we've already seen this option, don't add it to the list again. ----
2289 if (!OptionSet.insert(I->second).second) 0
2290 continue; 0
2291 ----
2292 Opts.push_back( 0
2293 std::pair(I->getKey().data(), I->second)); 0
2294 } ----
2295 ----
2296 // Sort the options list alphabetically. ----
2297 array_pod_sort(Opts.begin(), Opts.end(), OptNameCompare); 0
2298 } 0
2299 ----
2300 static void ----
2301 sortSubCommands(const SmallPtrSetImpl &SubMap, 0
2302 SmallVectorImpl> &Subs) { ----
2303 for (auto *S : SubMap) { 0
2304 if (S->getName().empty()) 0
2305 continue; 0
2306 Subs.push_back(std::make_pair(S->getName().data(), S)); 0
2307 } ----
2308 array_pod_sort(Subs.begin(), Subs.end(), SubNameCompare); 0
2309 } 0

2313 class HelpPrinter { ----
2314 protected: ----
2315 const bool ShowHidden; ----
2316 typedef SmallVector, 128> ----
2317 StrOptionPairVector; ----
2318 typedef SmallVector, 128> ----
2319 StrSubCommandPairVector; ----
2320 // Print the options. Opts is assumed to be alphabetically sorted. ----
2321 virtual void printOptions(StrOptionPairVector &Opts, size_t MaxArgLen) { 0
2322 for (size_t i = 0, e = Opts.size(); i != e; ++i) 0
2323 Opts[i].second->printOptionInfo(MaxArgLen); 0
2324 } 0
2325 ----
2326 void printSubCommands(StrSubCommandPairVector &Subs, size_t MaxSubLen) { 0
2327 for (const auto &S : Subs) { 0
2328 outs() << " " << S.first; 0
2329 if (!S.second->getDescription().empty()) { 0
2330 outs().indent(MaxSubLen - strlen(S.first)); 0
2331 outs() << " - " << S.second->getDescription(); 0
2332 } ----
2333 outs() << "\n"; 0
2334 } ----
2335 } 0
2336 ----
2337 public: ----
2338 explicit HelpPrinter(bool showHidden) : ShowHidden(showHidden) {} 8 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
2339 virtual ~HelpPrinter() = default; 8 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
2340 ----
2341 // Invoke the printer. ----
2342 void operator=(bool Value) { 0
2343 if (!Value) 0
2344 return; 0
2345 printHelp(); 0
2346 ----
2347 // Halt the program since help information was printed ----
2348 exit(0); 0
2349 } ----
2350 ----
2351 void printHelp() { 0
2352 SubCommand *Sub = GlobalParser->getActiveSubCommand(); 0
2353 auto &OptionsMap = Sub->OptionsMap; 0
2354 auto &PositionalOpts = Sub->PositionalOpts; 0
2355 auto &ConsumeAfterOpt = Sub->ConsumeAfterOpt; 0
2356 ----
2357 StrOptionPairVector Opts; 0
2358 sortOpts(OptionsMap, Opts, ShowHidden); 0
2359 ----
2360 StrSubCommandPairVector Subs; 0
2361 sortSubCommands(GlobalParser->RegisteredSubCommands, Subs); 0
2362 ----
2363 if (!GlobalParser->ProgramOverview.empty()) 0
2364 outs() << "OVERVIEW: " << GlobalParser->ProgramOverview << "\n"; 0
2365 ----
2366 if (Sub == &SubCommand::getTopLevel()) { 0
2367 outs() << "USAGE: " << GlobalParser->ProgramName; 0
2368 if (Subs.size() > 2) 0
2369 outs() << " [subcommand]"; 0
2370 outs() << " [options]"; 0
2371 } else { ----
2372 if (!Sub->getDescription().empty()) { 0
2373 outs() << "SUBCOMMAND '" << Sub->getName() 0
2374 << "': " << Sub->getDescription() << "\n\n"; 0
2375 } ----
2376 outs() << "USAGE: " << GlobalParser->ProgramName << " " << Sub->getName() 0
2377 << " [options]"; 0
2378 } ----
2379 ----
2380 for (auto *Opt : PositionalOpts) { 0
2381 if (Opt->hasArgStr()) 0
2382 outs() << " --" << Opt->ArgStr; 0
2383 outs() << " " << Opt->HelpStr; 0
2384 } ----
2385 ----
2386 // Print the consume after option info if it exists... ----
2387 if (ConsumeAfterOpt) 0
2388 outs() << " " << ConsumeAfterOpt->HelpStr; 0
2389 ----
2390 if (Sub == &SubCommand::getTopLevel() && !Subs.empty()) { 0
2391 // Compute the maximum subcommand length... ----
2392 size_t MaxSubLen = 0; 0
2393 for (size_t i = 0, e = Subs.size(); i != e; ++i) 0
2394 MaxSubLen = std::max(MaxSubLen, strlen(Subs[i].first)); 0
2395 ----
2396 outs() << "\n\n"; 0
2397 outs() << "SUBCOMMANDS:\n\n"; 0
2398 printSubCommands(Subs, MaxSubLen); 0
2399 outs() << "\n"; 0
2400 outs() << " Type \"" << GlobalParser->ProgramName 0
2401 << " --help\" to get more help on a specific " ----
2402 "subcommand"; 0
2403 } ----
2404 ----
2405 outs() << "\n\n"; 0
2406 ----
2407 // Compute the maximum argument length... ----
2408 size_t MaxArgLen = 0; 0
2409 for (size_t i = 0, e = Opts.size(); i != e; ++i) 0
2410 MaxArgLen = std::max(MaxArgLen, Opts[i].second->getOptionWidth()); 0
2411 ----
2412 outs() << "OPTIONS:\n"; 0
2413 printOptions(Opts, MaxArgLen); 0
2414 ----
2415 // Print any extra help the user has declared. ----
2416 for (const auto &I : GlobalParser->MoreHelp) 0
2417 outs() << I; 0
2418 GlobalParser->MoreHelp.clear(); 0
2419 } 0
2420 }; ----

2422 class CategorizedHelpPrinter : public HelpPrinter { ----
2423 public: ----
2424 explicit CategorizedHelpPrinter(bool showHidden) : HelpPrinter(showHidden) {} 4 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
2425 ----
2426 // Helper function for printOptions(). ----
2427 // It shall return a negative value if A's name should be lexicographically ----
2428 // ordered before B's name. It returns a value greater than zero if B's name ----
2429 // should be ordered before A's name, and it returns 0 otherwise. ----
2430 static int OptionCategoryCompare(OptionCategory *const *A, 0
2431 OptionCategory *const *B) { ----
2432 return (*A)->getName().compare((*B)->getName()); 0
2433 } ----
2434 ----
2435 // Make sure we inherit our base class's operator=() ----
2436 using HelpPrinter::operator=; ----
2437 ----
2438 protected: ----
2439 void printOptions(StrOptionPairVector &Opts, size_t MaxArgLen) override { 0
2440 std::vector SortedCategories; 0
2441 DenseMap> CategorizedOptions; 0
2442 ----
2443 // Collect registered option categories into vector in preparation for ----
2444 // sorting. ----
2445 for (OptionCategory *Category : GlobalParser->RegisteredOptionCategories) 0
2446 SortedCategories.push_back(Category); 0
2447 ----
2448 // Sort the different option categories alphabetically. ----
2449 assert(SortedCategories.size() > 0 && "No option categories registered!"); 0
2450 array_pod_sort(SortedCategories.begin(), SortedCategories.end(), 0
2451 OptionCategoryCompare); ----
2452 ----
2453 // Walk through pre-sorted options and assign into categories. ----
2454 // Because the options are already alphabetically sorted the ----
2455 // options within categories will also be alphabetically sorted. ----
2456 for (size_t I = 0, E = Opts.size(); I != E; ++I) { 0
2457 Option *Opt = Opts[I].second; 0
2458 for (auto &Cat : Opt->Categories) { 0
2459 assert(llvm::is_contained(SortedCategories, Cat) && 0
2460 "Option has an unregistered category"); ----
2461 CategorizedOptions[Cat].push_back(Opt); 0
2462 } ----
2463 } ----
2464 ----
2465 // Now do printing. ----
2466 for (OptionCategory *Category : SortedCategories) { 0
2467 // Hide empty categories for --help, but show for --help-hidden. ----
2468 const auto &CategoryOptions = CategorizedOptions[Category]; 0
2469 bool IsEmptyCategory = CategoryOptions.empty(); 0
2470 if (!ShowHidden && IsEmptyCategory) 0
2471 continue; 0
2472 ----
2473 // Print category information. ----
2474 outs() << "\n"; 0
2475 outs() << Category->getName() << ":\n"; 0
2476 ----
2477 // Check if description is set. ----
2478 if (!Category->getDescription().empty()) 0
2479 outs() << Category->getDescription() << "\n\n"; 0
2480 else ----
2481 outs() << "\n"; 0
2482 ----
2483 // When using --help-hidden explicitly state if the category has no ----
2484 // options associated with it. ----
2485 if (IsEmptyCategory) { 0
2486 outs() << " This option category has no options.\n"; 0
2487 continue; 0
2488 } ----
2489 // Loop over the options in the category and print. ----
2490 for (const Option *Opt : CategoryOptions) 0
2491 Opt->printOptionInfo(MaxArgLen); 0
2492 } ----
2493 } 0
2494 }; ----
